President Obama has proclaimed March 6-12, 2016 as National Consumer Protection Week in the United States. In his proclamation, he emphasizes the importance of ensuring hardworking families feel secure and confident in their financial situations. The President highlights the efforts his administration has made to protect consumers, including enacting Wall Street reform, implementing strong consumer protections, and proposing rules to combat abusive lending practices. He also discusses initiatives such as capping student loan payments and establishing a Student Aid Bill of Rights. The President encourages individuals to take steps to detect abuse and safeguard their personal data, and he promises to continue working to make online transactions more secure. He urges everyone to uphold the values of honesty and fair play and to ensure that hard work is rewarded. The President calls upon government officials, industry leaders, and advocates to share information about consumer protection and educate citizens about their rights.